@node Load
@title "Load"
Load
----

This loads in the previous results file.  This is important if you have just
edited a number by accident, and can't remember the original number, or you
have been loading the @{"Other Files" link OtherFiles}

See also @{"Load Other" link LoadOther}.
@endnode
@node LoadOther
@title "Load Other"
Load Other
----------

This is obtained by right mouse click on the "Load" icon.  From here you can
load up the @{"Other Files" link OtherFiles}
@endnode
@node Save
@title "Save"
Save
----

This saves both the previous results, and the last set of numbers you put
in, including the @{"date" link Date}.  If you are putting in more than one
week's worth of numbers, click save after each set you put in.

This now updates the @{"NL_Set ?, NL_Mac ? & NL_Set ? \ Mac ?" link OtherFiles} as
well as @{"NL_Weeks" link OtherFiles}.  
You can turn off updating in the @{"Preferences" link Prefs} screen.

A status line is shown under the load/save icons.

If you have loaded one of the @{"other files" link OtherFiles}, clicking on this option will save
the current file, but NOT CHANGE ANY OF THE OTHER FILES.

See also @{"Save As" link SaveAs}.
@endnode
@node SaveAs
@title "Save As"
Save As
-------

This is obtained by @{"RMB" link Abbrev} click on the @{"Save" link Save}
icon.  From here you can save the standard file under a different name, or
save one of the @{"other files" link OtherFiles}.
@endnode
@node Enter
@title "Enter Called Numbers/Show Added Numbers"
Enter Called Numbers
--------------------

After clicking on this you will be presented with a new screen, containing
seven boxes near the middle.  Type in each number from last Saturday's draw.
The number will change to the proper lottery colour.

If it disappears the number was not in the range 1 - 49.  Check the number
and type it in again.

You do not need to press return after each number, unless it is only one
figure (you can also type these in as 08 etc).  If you do you may skip the
ball set and machine.  (See next paragraph)

After typing in the numbers, you can enter the ball set and machine. These
are used to automatically generate some of the @{"Other Files" link OtherFiles}

The machine should be entered according to the abbreviations in the @{"prefs" link Prefs}
screen.

The machine name will be displayed after pressing the abbreviation letter.

If you have not typed in the ball set and/or machine, it is a good idea to
disable @{"NL_Set, NL_Set \ Mac (NL_SM) and/or NL_Mac" link OtherFiles} in @{"Prefs" link Prefs} before saving.

There are two other options on this screen - @{" From File " link FromFile}
                                             @{" Create All " link Create}

If you click anywhere else you will be taken back to the @{"main menu" link MainMenu}
The numbers you have typed in will be ignored, so no files will be updated
with these numbers.

After typing in all the information the pointer will change into a @{"mouse" link Mouse}
(magic trick!).  You then have two options:

Left mouse button:  Accept
Right mouse button: Cancel (ignores numbers)

If the printer is on (see @{"Printer" link Printer}, it will print the
current @{"date" link Date} and the numbers, so you can check them.

Show Added Numbers
------------------

This appears on the @{"main menu" link MainMenu} and @{"pull-down" link PullDown} menus if you have entered numbers
but not saved them.

It shows the numbers and you have two options: 

Accept (@{"LMB" link Abbrev}) - Returns you to the main menu
Cancel (@{"RMB" link Abbrev}) - Ignores the numbers and changes the current file back
@endnode
@node FromFile
@title "From File"
This option will present you with a file requestor.  You can load and use a
previous week file (eg "Week 1") or create your own.

If you create your own file, the file name must begin with "Week" and be in
the directory S:NL_Data.  It must be in the following format:

NL1    - File Format Version, keep it as NL1
 1    }
 2    }
 3    }    These are the numbers from the draw
 4    }
 5    }    They must start with a single space.
 6    }
 7    }
1      - This the the ball set number used in the draw
A      - This is the first letter of the machine used, in CAPITALS

Each line should end with a Ctrl-M character.  If you can save text with
Carriage Return (CR) and Line Feeds (LF) then this should work OK.

After loading the file, it will be displayed.  The left mouse button accepts
the file, the right mouse button cancels and ignores it.

The ball set and machine are used in updating the @{"Other Files" link OtherFiles}

YOU CAN USE THIS FEATURE TO USE THE PROGRAM FOR OTHER LOTTERIES:

Type the numbers into a file, if it uses less than seven numbers, just make
the extra ones '0'.  If the lottery uses numbers higher than 49 then,
obviously, you can't use this program.
@endnode
@node Create
@title "Create All Files"
This option uses all the "Week ?" files to create all the @{"Other Files" link OtherFiles}.
It is found in the @{"Enter Called Numbers" link Enter} screen.

Check the @{"preferences" link Prefs} screen to see/change which files will be updated.
This is useful if there is only one file which needs creating.

A status screen is displayed to show you how far it has got.  If you are
using the program from a floppy disk, it may take some time to create all
the files, especially if you have a lot of week's worth of numbers.

You should not need to use this option unless something makes one of the
files unuseable, or another "Other File" is available which wasn't in the
version you were using before.  You may need to use it if you enter and
save some numbers wrongly, but don't realise until afterwards.

You can copy the "Week ?" files from your old NL_Winner disk onto your new
one, using @{"NL_Merge" link NLMerge}, then click on "Create All" to create the new files,
setting them in @{"Prefs" link Prefs}.

@{fg shadow}@{b}WARNING!@{ub}@{fg text} All files to be re-compiled will be
deleted, and so will files which begin with the same first five letters.

If you have created your own @{"Other File" link OtherFiles}, copy it across
to another disk, or @{"print" link Printer} out the @{"frequency table" link Show} for it, first.  You can
then copy it back or re-enter the data using @{"edit" link Editing} if it gets mistaken for another file.
@endnode 
@node Prediction
@title "Predicted Numbers"
Prediction
----------

The most important option.  This is the one which could win you ŁŁŁ's. 

After clicking on the icon, it will display seven lots of six boxes.

The first two rows are the same prediction calculated different ways ("Hot
Numbers")  The third row shows the numbers which are the same in the first
two rows.  If this row is full, these are numbers which you should
definately put on your lottery playslip.

The fourth, fifth and sixth rows are a repeat of the first three rows, but
with a different method of prediction.

The seventh row is a sequence of random numbers.  The theory behind the
random numbers is that a computer is more likely to pick the same ones as a
lottery machine than us. (You can also choose random numbers using @{"NL_BootUp" link NLBootUp})

The random numbers work "normally" (as above) only if you have no numbers
in memory.  (You can load up the @{"NL_Random" link OtherFiles} file to
achieve this or use the @{"Clear" link Clear} menu item.

If you do have some numbers in memory, it does a random sequence of the
predicted numbers.

Clicking on a row of numbers with the @{"LMB" link Abbrev} will bring up the
@{"Show Called Numbers" link Show} @{"Stats" link ShowStats} screen.
(Make sure the @{"Export" link Mouse} pointer is showing first!)
Clicking with the @{"RMB" link Abbrev} will bring up the @{"Wheeling" link
Wheeling} screen.
@endnode
@node Show
After clicking on "Show called numbers" you can go to any of three areas.
The "Menu" screen is the one which will appear first (unless you have
accessed this screen before, or set a different screen with the @{"Prefs" link Prefs}
