@endnode
@node ShowTable
@title "Show Previously Called Numbers - Table"
Show Called Numbers (Table)
-------------------

This displays a screen full of numbers.  The ones under "No." show the
number, the one to the right of it shows the amount of times it has been
called.

You can edit this information.  See @{"editing files" link Editing}

At the bottom of the screen is a row of boxes.  This is the @{"previous
week" link PrevWeek}
section.

At the top of the screen is a @{"Screen" link ShowMenu} button. This moves you to different
information screens.
@endnode
@node ShowWheel
@title "Show Previously Called Numbers - Wheeling"
Show Called Numbers (Wheeling)
-------------------

This area of @{"show called numbers" link Show} displays a grid.  The lines
labelled A - G are the numbers you should use.  The line labelled ORIG shows
all seven numbers.  You can enter your own numbers by editing the row at
the bottom of the screen, or by clicking on a line with the @{"RMB" link Abbrev} in the
@{"prediction" link Prediction} screen.

The @{"Screen" link ShowMenu} button at the top of the screen brings up the
@{"Show Called Numbers Menu" link ShowMenu}.
@endnode
@node ShowGraph
@title "Show Previously Called Numbers - Graph"
Show Called Numbers (Graph)
-------------------

The graph area of @{"Show called numbers" link Show} displays a frequency graph of the
called numbers.

A number with no bar does not symbolise that that number has not been
called.  It shows that that number has been called the least number of
times.  This is in order to try and stop the graph disappearing off the
top of the screen.

A bar with a ^ at the top shows that the bar goes off the top of the graph.

An empty column with a "v" at the bottom (which means it won't be empty!)
symbolises that the bar is lower than the lowest point of the graph.

Down the side of the graph are two arrows.  The top arrow moves up the
graph to show a higher point, and the down arrow shows a lower point.

At the bottom of the screen is the @{"previous weeks" link PrevWeek} section.
This information can be edited - See @{"Editing Files" link Editing}

At the top of the screen is the button @{"Screen" link ShowMenu}.  This moves
you to different information screens.
@endnode
@node ShowStats
@title "Show Previously Called Numbers - Stats"
Show Called Numbers (Stats)
-------------------

This section used to be the NL_Extras program, @{"NL_Stats" link NLStats}.

When you click on "stats" the computer works out the following for the
numbers shown in the @{"previous weeks" link PrevWeek} section at the bottom of the screen:

Mean (Average)
Sum (Add up numbers)
High (Highest Number)
Low (Lowest Number)
Range (Spread of numbers)
Standard Deviation (Average distance from the mean)

Under all these is a "graph" showing the spread of the numbers on a line.
The "graph" to the right shows the spread of numbers on a lottery playslip.

If you wish to enter your own numbers, instead of using data from a previous
week, you can edit the "Week 0" information.  It is best to move back to the
@{"table" link ShowTable} or @{"graph" link ShowGraph} section using the @{"Screen" link ShowMenu} button at the top of the screen to type in
your numbers.  You can then go to the stats screen to look at the
information.  You can also go to the @{"prediction" link Prediction} screen, and click on the
row of numbers you wish to use with the @{"LMB" link Abbrev}.

PLEASE NOTE: A 0 (zero) in the previous week information is counted as being
an "end of line" character.  If you only want to enter three numbers, the
fourth should be a zero.

If the first number is zero, the computer will use the whole file instead of
just one week.
@endnode
@node PrevWeek
@title "Numbers called in previous weeks"
At the bottom of the @{"show called numbers" link Show} screen is a row of numbers.
These are the numbers which were called in any previous draw.

To the left of these is a box which shows the date of the draw and the week
number.  The week number is not always the week of the draw, it is the
number of draws you have put in. 

To the right of that is a small box possibly containing two letters or one
letter and one number.  The top letter/number is the ball set used that
week, and the bottom is the machine.

To look at a different week, see @{"searching weeks" link Search}

Click anywhere else, using the left mouse button, to exit from this screen.

You can edit all this information - see @{"Editing Files" link Editing}
@endnode
@node Search
@title "Search options"
The search option can be found in @{"Show Called Numbers" link Show}.

To view a different week, just click with the @{"LMB" link Abbrev} on the box
containing "Week ...".  You can now enter a new week number.

Alternatively, you can use the two arrow buttons to move through the weeks
one at a time. (This could take some time if you have hundreds of weeks
worth of data)
If you click on one of the arrows with the right mouse button, you will move
to either Week 0 or the last week entered.

To search for a week, when you know the date but not the week number, click
with the @{"LMB" link Abbrev} on the date.  Now enter the new date.  It must
be typed EXACTLY as it appears in the file.

In the bottom-left of the @{"frequency of results" link Show} table, there
are two buttons, one showing "<", the other ">".  These indicate the
direction of the search.  After clicking on one of the buttons, the search
will start.

(">" = forwards, "<" = backwards)

@{b}THE SEARCH ALWAYS STARTS FROM THE WEEK CURRENTLY DISPLAYED.@{ub}

When a week containing the date is found, it will be displayed.  You can now
@{"edit" link Editing} the file, return to the @{"main menu" link MainMenu},
or continue searching.

To continue searching, just click on the arrow showing the direction you
want to search.

The method used above is exactly the same for searching for ball sets and
machines (except you click in a different box).

When doing searchs on the results, the method is slightly different.

Click on the FIRST numbers box, and enter a number.

NOTE: When typing in 2-figure numbers (eg. 22, 43) DO NOT PRESS RETURN. When
typing in 1-figure numbers (eg. 1, 4) you can either press return or type
them in as 2-figure numbers (eg 01, 04).

After typing in the first number, you can start the search (by pressing
"return" or clicking the @{"LMB" link Abbrev}), or type in another number.

YOU MUST CHECK THAT THE NUMBER HAS ENTERED (CHANGED TO THE PROPER COLOUR),
BEFORE STARTING THE SEARCH.

When you start the search, the two buttons will change to "ONE" and "WIN".

If you click on "ONE", the computer will search for weeks which contain just
one of the numbers you typed in. (Same as old OR option)

If you click on "WIN", the computer will search for weeks containing at least
three numbers you typed in.

If you typed in less than three numbers, you must select "ONE".

The buttons will then change back to "<" and ">".  Click on the arrow
pointing in the direction you wish to search in.

When found, you can do as described above.

To clear a search, and change the buttons back to "forwards and backwards",
click on the first numbers box, and press return.

You can use the search options, together with @{"From File" link FromFile},
to create your own @{"\"Other File\"" link OtherFiles}.
@endnode
@node Editing
@title "Editing Files"
To edit any information in the @{"Show Called Numbers" link Show} @{"TABLE" link ShowTable} screen,
and the @{"Previous Weeks" link PrevWeek} section, use the right mouse button.

If you click in the box containing the date, using the @{"RMB" link Abbrev},
you can enter a new date.  This is no longer saved to the file automatically,
you must click on the SMALL @{"save" link SmSave} button under the line of numbers.
These can also be edited by clicking on them with the @{"RMB" link Abbrev}

The machine and set can be edited as well, by clicking on them with the @{"RMB" link Abbrev}.

The full list of numbers can also be edited by clicking on the one you want
to edit with the @{"RMB" link Abbrev}.

You will then need to click on the main @{"save" link Save} to save the edited
list.
@endnode
@node Quit
@title "Quit"
Quit
----

Quits the program.  It will NOT ask you if you want to save.
@endnode
@node Printer
@title "Printing"
Printing
--------

To print out screens, press the "P" key.
@endnode
@node Date
@title "Changing the Date"
Date
----

Clicking on the line which includes the date and week number will ask you to
input a new date.  This can be in any form but cannot exceed eight
characters.
@endnode
@node Info
@title "Info... Menu option"
This displays a small window, similar to the help window, near the top of
the screen:

FILE: Shows the currently loaded file's name
FILE FORMAT: NL1, NL2, NL3, NL4 or NL5.  NL4 is similar to NL2, but versions
of this program which load NL2 DO NOT load NL4.  This is true of all the
file formats.  The lowest version which can save/load the file is shown
in brackets. (Versions may be approximate)  

Note: Since NL5 (V2.0) I have changed the program slightly so newer file
formats (NL6 etc.) may load into the program (but with a slight loss of
information if saved out again).

NUMBERS: Number of numbers in memory WEEKS: Equivalent number of weeks
