@node Winning
@title "Improving Your Chances Of Winning"
As everyone (well, nearly everyone) knows, there is a 14 million-to-one
@{"chance" link NLOdds} of winning the jackpot.  But did you know that, out of the six main
numbers called, there are 20 different ways of winning Ł10?

The program NL_Winner is designed to improve the chance of:

(a) winning the jackpot (or any other amount) and
(b) finding one of the 20 different ways of winning Ł10.

It does this by predicting likely numbers for the next draw.  Obviously, the
more numbers input, the better the prediction.

The main file, Numbers, is very general.  It contains numbers called using
all ball sets and machines.

@{"NL_NoBonus" link OtherFiles} is almost the same, but for people who think the bonus number is
of no importance.

The @{"NL_Set" link OtherFiles} files contain numbers just from one ball
set, but different machines.  These files should be more accurate than the
Numbers file.

The @{"NL_Machine" link OtherFiles} files contain numbers from one machine,
but different ball sets.  These files should be about the same accuracy as
NL_Set.

The @{"NL_SM" link OtherFiles} files contain very specialised
results.  They include numbers only from a certain combination of ball set
and machine.  This is likely to be the most accurate prediction, but you
will have to spend around Ł24 per week.  However, if you use the program
@{"NL_SetMac" link NLSetMac}, you could just use the suggested file.

Think about this... You spend nearly 14 million pounds on lottery tickets.
You (obviously) win the jackpot.  You only win 1 million pounds, as you had
to share it with 8 other people.  Congratulations! You've just lost 13
million pounds!

The file @{"NL_FirstBall" link OtherFiles} should offer an even more accurate
prediction, as it contains balls which have come out when all the balls have
exactly the same probability of coming out [1/49].  This file can be split
into separate Set, Mac & Set/Mac files if required.

The file @{"NL_Weeks" link NLWeeks} is a bit different.  It contains the
last week each number was called.  If a number has not been called for a
long time it is likely to come up again soon.
If a number has very recently been called, it is likely to come up again.
Once, the same number came up for three weeks running, and on several
occasions the @{"same number" link Success} has come up twice on two
consectutive weeks.

The @{"wheeling" link ShowWheel} screen gives you seven lines of similar
numbers.  This improves your chances of winning more smaller prizes.

@endnode
